DESCRIPTION: Visually inspect the power supply module’s green LED, its series resistor, and especially the LED holder/socket to see if there is any sign that the LED has been miswired or that the holder pins are shorted together, effectively bypassing the LED/resistor and possibly misrouting the positive and negative rails leaving the module.,
RESULT: The PSU Status LED (green) is lit and shows no observable internal fault, and its series resistor also shows no observable internal fault. The Power Supply Module has no observable internal fault. No visual indication of LED miswiring or shorted holder/socket was found.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-16 12:14:10 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Interconnection between Control Module 1 and Control Module 2'] hypothesis_explanation='All active modules and the load have been replaced and verified good, and the PSU output polarity is correct. Continuity tests show that: (1) PSU (+) and (−) each reach Control Module 1 and leave it correctly to its “Output (+1)” and “Output (−1)” terminals; (2) the cabling and continuity from Control Module 2 onward to the load are correct and form two sound rails; but (3) there is no end‑to‑end continuity from Control Output (+1) to the downstream (+) line, and the path from Control Output (−1) to the downstream (−) line is resistive rather than a solid conductor. Since both Module 1 and Module 2 have been confirmed not faulty internally, the only remaining element that can produce this specific pattern is the way the fast‑connect terminals/cables between these two modules are mated: at least one of the two conductors in that link is plugged to the wrong counterpart or partially open, so that the series chain is broken between Module 1 and Module 2. This single mis‑connected inter-module link explains why no control LEDs (2–8) or the load ever see 12 V despite a healthy PSU and modules.'
