2026-04-16 12:14:54 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply module output terminals / fast-connection pair'] hypothesis_explanation='All ten functional modules (PSU, 8 control modules, load module) and all inter‑module cables have been verified or even replaced without restoring operation. Continuity tests show: \n- PSU output cables individually provide correct 12 V polarity.\n- Control Module 1 has good continuity from its input to its output, and all downstream modules form a continuous + and − rail to the load.\n- Yet, when the system is assembled normally, the load module input sees 0 V and the lamp sees 0 V, even with all switches ON and the PSU LED lit.\n\nThis combination implies that the fault is not inside any module or cable run but at the interface where the PSU connects into the chain. The most plausible remaining defect is a configuration/connection error at the PSU’s fast‑connection pair (e.g., the two conductors from the PSU are mated to the wrong counterpart in the first cable harness or are not actually completing the series loop despite appearing continuous in earlier point‑to‑point tests). This would allow the PSU LED to light (since it is wired directly across the internal battery) but leave the external series loop to the load open or improperly referenced, giving 0 V at the load with all modules otherwise healthy.\n\nThus the root cause is a faulty/misconfigured connection at the power supply module output terminals/fast‑connector pair, not any of the individual control or load modules.'
